    <subexercises>
      <title>Challenge</title>
      <exercise>
        <!-- Kara's challenge problem -->
        <webwork>
          <pg-code>
            $little = random(2,10,2);
            $medium = $little+1;
            $medium2 = $medium+1;
            do {$big = random($medium2,15,1);} until ($big % $little != 0);
            $steepest = Formula("$big/$little");
            $shallowest = Formula("$little/$big");
          </pg-code>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Fill in the variables <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>,
              and <m>C</m> in <m>Ax + By = C</m> with the numbers <m><var name="$little"/>,
              <var name="$medium"/></m> and <m><var name="$big"/></m>.
              You may only use each number once.
              <ol label="a.">
                <li>
                  <p>
                    For the steepest possible slope,
                    <m>A</m> must be <var name="$big" width="4" />,
                    <m>B</m> must be <var name="$little" width="4" />,
                    and <m>C</m> must be <var name="$medium" width="4" />.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    For the shallowest possible slope,
                    <m>A</m> must be <var name="$little" width="4" />,
                    <m>B</m> must be <var name="$big" width="4" />,
                    and <m>C</m> must be <var name="$medium" width="4" />.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <ol label="a.">
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Let's put <m> Ax + By = C </m> into slope-intercept form.
                    Then, the equation becomes <m> y = \frac{-A}{B}x + \frac{C}{B} </m>.
                    To make the steepest slope possible,
                    we must maximize the fraction <m>\frac{A}{B}</m>.
                    The possibilities are <m> \frac{<var name="$little"/>}{<var name="$medium"/>}, \frac{<var name="$little"/>}{<var name="$big"/>}, \frac{<var name="$medium"/>}{<var name="$little"/>}, \frac{<var name="$medium"/>}{<var name="$big"/>}, \frac{<var name="$big"/>}{<var name="$little"/>}</m>,
                    and <m> \frac{<var name="$big"/>}{<var name="$medium"/>} </m>.
                    The biggest of these is <m> \frac{<var name="$big"/>}{<var name="$little"/>} </m>.
                    Thus, <m>A</m> must equal <var name="$big"/>,
                    <m>B</m> must equal <var name="$little"/>, and <m>C</m> must equal <var name="$medium"/>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    To make the shallowest slope possible,
                    we must minimize the fraction <m>\frac{A}{B}</m>.
                    The smallest of the possible fractions is <m> \frac{<var name="$little"/>}{<var name="$big"/>} </m>.
                    Thus, <m>A</m> must equal <var name="$little"/>,
                    <m>B</m> must equal <var name="$big"/>, and <m>C</m> must equal <var name="$medium"/>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </webwork>
      </exercise>
